{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0184F3GEJ2i8tvWpmYP2zagY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the issue clearly:\n\n1. The Prometheus config only has a `prometheus` job scraping `localhost:9090` - it's not scraping RabbitMQ at all.\n2. The RabbitMQ pods expose metrics on port 15692 at `/metrics`.\n3. There's a headless service `rabbitmq-headless` that I can use to address individual pods by their DNS names.\n\nThe fix is to update the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add a scrape job for RabbitMQ. I need to target all 3 pods. I have a few options:\n- Use static configs with the individual pod DNS names via the headless service, pointing each to `rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`, `rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`, and `rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n\nThis approach works with native Kubernetes resources and doesn't require any CRDs.\n\nNow I need to reload Prometheus after updating the ConfigMap. Since the deployment has `--web.enable-lifecycle` enabled, I can trigger a reload by hitting the `/-/reload` endpoint rather than restarting the pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":736,"cache_read_input_tokens":30137,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":736},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"97dcffb0-53fe-45a5-8d89-0500ffcbe661","uuid":"f3b5a4c7-66c5-4c03-8753-6b6a945fe91e","request_id":"req_011CcdFx35GsLza3e4pomWLd"}
